A future without precedent
JERUSALEM – At nearly 90 years of age, I can no longer recall a time when the past was so insignificant in shaping political decisions.
None of the significant developments of the present were foreseen by anyone.
Experts did indeed examine the past, but due to their confinement within old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Given the dynamic complexity of the world today, in which, due to a rapidly changing and scientifically grounded global economy, an increasing number of events are interdependent, we are unable to predict the future on the basis of a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty lies in the fact that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is waning. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome because science and technology are boundless.
Global corporations operating worldwide want to pursue their business interests globally, thereby suffering a loss of sovereignty on the one hand, but also weakening racism and prejudices as well as, to a significant extent, nationalism on the other.
As a result of this transformation, the fate of this world now rests in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically adept than their parents and connected to one another through social networks that transcend national borders, linguistic barriers, and different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people are also at the forefront of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring", the tent protests in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark no clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
This generation knows that the way states and economies are currently run is unsuitable for the new times.
