In the Arab world, primarily Islamist extremists are hijacking the protests of the young generation and thereby stealing their revolution.
Israel has positively responded to the will of the young generation, but it cannot and should not intervene in the events of the Arab world.
We are at heart with the rebellious young people and their legitimate aspiration for freedom and basic rights, which should enable them to make their voices heard, choose their political leadership, and support themselves financially.
The Israelis wait for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, for the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is a serious concern that the politically well-organized extremists will attempt to win control over less well-organized Liberals in elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer genuine solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current societal upheavals threaten their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
Only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others when it comes to achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, for its success lies in the fact that the country began with absolutely nothing.
When we returned to our homeland, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. As a result, we now have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita.
About 95 percent of our country's agriculture relies on high technology.
We consume less water and yet achieve higher yields per square meter of cultivated land than any other country in the world.
What others achieve in Israel can also be achieved elsewhere.
We are more than happy to offer our assistance wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything within our power to bring an end to the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to dominate another people, and that is not its destiny.
We are genuinely interested in creating a Palestinian state that coexists peacefully alongside Israel, the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, as resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing the extremists who seek to manipulate civic movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these aspirations by offering incentives to countries that strive for freedom and progress.
Decisive and pioneering political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially Iran is a source of moral decay, where extremism is promoted and reforms are obstructed, where legitimate protests by its own citizens are brutally suppressed and where it works against the courageous Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
The Iranian regime resorts to proxies to instigate terror against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, Lebanon, and Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, its leaders could shake the Middle East and further fuel extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
However, not only Israel is threatened. The Iranian regime poses a threat to peace and stability around the world.
The democracies of this world have vowed that they will not allow Iran to obtain nuclear weapons. It is their duty to uphold this pledge before it is too late.
Beyond these immediate challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children for dealing with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant to predicting the future, education must provide all children with the opportunity to unlock their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children to creativity and innovation.
Self-actualization is just as important as free speech.
I am writing this article at 88 years old, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and frequently constrains the courage needed to face the future and create a unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back has no meaning.
